Part II - PISA 2018 Database¶

by Nguyen Thi Thuy¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this explanatory section, I will discuss the key factors affecting students' overall literacy.

Dataset Overview and Executive Summary¶

The 2018 PISA School Dataset was constructed and organized into SAS and SPSS files. PISA, an acronym for "Programme for International Student Assessment," is a triennial assessment covering reading, mathematics, and science literacy that is taken by 15 year-old students. In 2018, PISA involved 79 countries and 600,000+ students worldwide.

The original file 'CY7_MS_CMB_STU_QQQ.sav' downloaded from webite https://www.oecd.org/pisa/data/2018database/ is too big that my computer can read. So, I extract useful columns that are used in this project.

My dataset includes 612004 rows and 34 columns.

Following is a summary of findings that my visualizations will support.

  1. The Grade Distribution
  2. The Overall literacy
  3. The Country where has the highest Overall Literacy
  4. Relationship between Internet connection and Overall Literacy
  5. Highest Parental Occupational Status affect Overall Literacy and Class Repeated
  6. Internet Connection affects Class Repeated and Overall Literacy

Relationship between Internet_Connection and Overall Literacy¶

In [34]:
df_pisa.boxplot(column = 'Overall_Literacy', by = 'Internet_Connection')
plt.xticks(rotation =15)
plt.xlabel('Internet_Connection')
plt.ylabel('Overall_Literacy')
Out[34]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Overall_Literacy')

We can see that, the Overall_Literacy is affected by the internet connection. The Overall_Literacy is highest at student group that they use once or twice a month and lowest at student group that they use everyday.

Relationship between Grade and Overall Literacy¶

In [35]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[1]

plt.xlabel('Grade');
plt.ylabel('Overall Literacy');

The variables Grade measured on a scale of -4.0 to 3.0 and Overall Literacy are analyzed. There is a strong positive correlation between the 2 factors. Scatter plot was not used as the plot of choice due to the discrete yet continuous nature of the Grade factor.

Visualization 3¶

Highest Parental Occupational Status vs Overall Literacy and Class Repeated¶

In [36]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df_pisa, hue = 'Class_repeated', height = 12)
g.map(plt.scatter, 'Highest_parental_occu_status', 'Overall_Literacy', alpha=1)
plt.title("Parent's Highest Occupational Status and its effect on Overall Literacy of Students and Repeated Class")
plt.xlabel('Highest Parental Occupational Status')
plt.ylabel('Overall Literacy')
g.add_legend(title ='Class Repeated?');
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 16});

As the Parents' occupational status increase so does the student's overall literacy, with that less and less students have repeated a class. The right side of the plot has majority of students who did not repeat a class whereas, as the parents' occupational status decrease so does the student's overall literacy, with that more and more students repeated a grade.

Highest Parental Occupational Status affects Overall Literacy and Grade¶

In [37]:
plt.figure(figsize = [24, 16])
plt.scatter(data = df_pisa, x = 'Highest_parental_occu_status', y = 'Overall_Literacy', c = 'Grade',
            cmap = 'icefire_r', alpha=1)
plt.title("Parent's Highest Occupational Status and its effect on Overall Literacy of Students and Grade")
plt.xlabel('Highest Parental Occupational Status')
plt.ylabel('Overall Literacy')
plt.colorbar(label = 'Grade');

We can see that the student's overall literacy increase as the Parents' occupational status increase. The right side of the plot has majority of students who are in the country’s modal grade if not above the modal grade. Whereas, as the parents' occupational status decrease so does the student's overall literacy, with that more and more students are below the modal grade.

Internet Connection affects Class Repeated and Overall Literacy¶

In [38]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df_pisa, col = 'Internet_Connection', col_wrap=2, height = 6)
g.map(sb.boxplot, 'Class_repeated', 'Overall_Literacy', color='darkred');
g.axes[0].set_title("No");
g.axes[1].set_title("Yes, but I don't use it");
g.axes[2].set_title("Yes, and I use it");
g.axes[3].set_title("Once or twice a month");
g.axes[4].set_title("Once or twice a week");

An observation found here is that students had repeated a grade and used internet connection had a higher overall literacy compared to students who repeated or not repeated a class and they either had no internet connection or they had internet connection but didnt use it.
